Installation
1. Clone the repository
git clone https://github.com/YOUR_USERNAME/trading-bot.git
cd trading-bot
2. Create and activate a virtual environment
macOS / Linux
python3 -m venv .venv
source .venv/bin/activate
Windows
python -m venv .venv
.venv\Scripts\activate
3. Install dependencies
pip install -r requirements.txt
Environment Variables

Create a local .env file or export these variables in your shell:

export ANTHROPIC_API_KEY="your_api_key_here"
export IB_HOST="127.0.0.1"
export IB_PORT="7497"
export IB_CLIENT_ID="1"
export IB_ACCOUNT="YOUR_PAPER_ACCOUNT"

If ANTHROPIC_API_KEY is not set, the bot should fall back to the internal rule-based engine.

Interactive Brokers Setup

Start TWS or IB Gateway first.

Recommended paper ports
TWS Paper: 7497
TWS Live: 7496
IB Gateway Paper: 4002
In TWS

Go to:

Edit → Global Configuration → API → Settings

Enable:

Enable ActiveX and Socket Clients
Allow connections from localhost only

Use the correct socket port and make sure Read-Only API is OFF if you want order placement enabled.

Configuration

Most settings live in config.py.

Main sections:

IBKRConfig → host, port, client ID, account
TimeConfig → allowed trading windows and timezone
IndicatorConfig → bar size, lookback, EMA settings, VWAP
OptionsConfig → option type, moneyness, premium cap
RiskConfig → stop loss, daily max loss, trade count limits
AIConfig → Claude model and behavior instructions
BotConfig → top-level bot settings including paper/live mode
Running the Bot

Start TWS or IB Gateway, then run:

python bot.py

Typical runtime flow:

Connect to Interactive Brokers
Pull recent QQQ bars
Compute indicators
Detect a trade setup
Evaluate through Claude or fallback rules
Pass the trade through risk checks
Submit an order if approved
Sleep and repeat on the configured loop interval
Simulation and Backtesting
Simulate the current trading day
python simulate_today.py
Run a historical backtest
python backtest.py
Inspect account information
python find_account.py
Safety Notes
Start with paper trading only
Do not hardcode API keys or account IDs in source code
Do not commit .env, logs, installers, or virtual environments
Validate option selection carefully before any live testing
Monitor every paper trade before considering real capital deployment
Recommended Improvements

Before using this as a serious live-trading system, consider adding:

.env loading with python-dotenv
structured logging
unit tests
better exception handling around broker disconnects
trade journal output (CSV / SQLite)
notifications (Slack / Telegram)
market-hours validation
stricter live-trading safeguards
better option contract selection verification
